Dance With Dani 4.12.22 🌹 

You would’ve loved yesterday so much, and that’s always the best, and the worst part. To be in a London dance studio we spent so many years in together, with Tom and Bowie, your family, closest friends and dance community all there to celebrate in your memory, was painfully raw and difficult, but beautiful too. I realised in various moments throughout the day, just how much you will continue to inspire forever more. Dancers for years to come will aspire to be like you, and rightly so, you and your career were the ‘best of the best’. The talent, the respect you earned, the love you gave, the kindness to any and every dancer, the work ethic, the memories, the friendships, the years we all spent together pursuing our passions and living out our dreams alongside each other, all felt so deeply yesterday. 
I feel so privileged to have shared this part of our lives so closely together. Moments on stages, stadiums and everything in between, our friends created something special on and off stage, and that will never leave us. We are closer than ever, and to dance alongside each other again after most of us have hung up our dancing shoes, was an honour felt by us all. 

It is true that love lives on, and I hope we made you proud yesterday, and every day going forward. I will always do my very best. 

Grief, and in this respect, traumatic grief is something that has changed me and the people I love forever. These are the darkest of days, but yesterday brought light and when those moments arrive, we hold them close and cherish them dearly whilst they last. 

Thank You to everyone who has supported, donated and shown love, it means the world and we are all very grateful for the kindness. 

Life is precious.

To my beautiful Danielle, I love you x 💔🤍

I absolutely love the words below. I hope they can be felt by you too:

Why do we start a new year, with promises to improve?
Who began this tradition of never-ending pressure?
I say, the end of a year, should be filled with congratulation, for all we survived. 
And I say a new year should start with promises to be kinder to ourselves, to understand better just how much we bear, as humans on this exhausting treadmill of life.

And if we are to promise more, let’s pledge to rest, before our bodies force us. 
Let’s pledge to stop, and drink in life as it happens.
Let’s pledge to strip away a layer of perfection to reveal the flawed and wondrous humanity we truly are inside.

Why start another year, gifted to us on this earth, with demands on our already over-strained humanity. 
When we could be learning to accept, that we were always supposed to be imperfect.
And that is where the beauty lives, actually.
And if we can only find that beauty, we would also find peace.

I wish you peace in 2023.
Everything else is all just a part of it.
Let it be so.

@donnaashworthwords

FIRST CLASS BACK @onepeloton 🎉

…and what an eventful journey to the studio it was 🤣. From train strikes and protests, to running through London, AND a pigeon flying straight into the side of my head 🤢, I literally just made it, and I’m so pleased I did so that we could celebrate the music of the coolest man on the planet, Mr @nilerodgers. I felt the love today. Honestly, I felt really apprehensive ahead of todays ride. It’s a big platform and I’ve allowed myself to be vulnerable with you all, and today felt a bit like my first day at school, and that’s all a lot for so many reasons, but you know what, this was a milestone that felt so far away at one point, and here I am on the other side of it. F**k yeah! 🎉 Your kindness, and your support is beyond anything I could’ve imagined, and to have over 8.5k of you joining LIVE, and showing each other love in the moment is what it’s all about. On the bike, it’ll always be about YOU, and I’m so happy we got to sparkle together today! ✨
The captions are long these days, so it’s in the carousel along with pics ❤️✨

How my ‘Love Day’ looked this year…
It started with radiotherapy 💪🏼 (how romantic 🤣😩) but then, I honestly just had one of the purest moments on the bike I’ve ever had. Taking the opportunity to use my class to share YOUR messages of love from member to member felt fulfilling, and warming, and perfect on a day like today. I’m more of a loving all year round kinda girl, but the little nudge to share more love today is ok with me. I’ve been in bits all day reading your shoutouts to someone in your life who deserves it. From family, and friends, to lovers and pets, we had it all. I’m never usually lost for words, but I can’t articulate how special that felt. Just a really honest bubble of love together. 🥹❤️

One of my (incredible) cancer nurses told me just after I was diagnosed that ‘cancer is as much of a mental game, as it is physical’.

The conversation was had in such a blurry, terrifying time, and yet it has always remained a crystal clear moment to me. It ignited a mindset in me that has felt like my superpower ever since. 

The apprehension I felt ahead of posting publicly about my diagnosis was pretty sky high. I knew I was ready to share, and I hoped by doing so I could raise awareness and make a difference somehow, but going from just my closest friends and family knowing, to a lot more people knowing, felt daunting. 

The moment after sharing, @benjaminalldis and I sang Diana Ross’s ‘I’m coming out’ and then off we went to Dopamine Land - An exhibition that boosts your happy emotions. Perfect!

The reason I say all this is: We chose happiness on an otherwise massively daunting day, and it felt freeing. There’s been SO much that I have had little control over, but mindset is totally within my control. It’s an inside job, it makes such a huge difference to how you approach anything in life, and it’s well worth working on ❤️

❤️ "Leanne was sitting in a corridor waiting to discuss her results with a consultant, when a cancer nurse came and quietly sat beside her. 

"'I was so horrible to that nurse. I was like, ‘Why are you here? Go away.’ I was so unprepared. I thought, this can’t be happening...'

"Leanne was diagnosed with early, triple positive breast cancer – slow growing, but still aggressive, which meant she was now hearing the words ‘chemotherapy, surgery, radiotherapy.’ 

"She told her family and close friends and asked them to keep the news private. I was one of those trusted with this awful secret. And just to add to our pain and alarm for our friend, she made a decision that still floors me: she was going to keep teaching her Peloton classes, around her weekly bouts of chemotherapy."

In January 2023, Peloton instructor Leanne Hainsby revealed that she was battling breast cancer. In that emotional post, the 35-year-old said she was sharing her story to raise awareness, especially since a doctor initially told her that “everything was ok” when she first got her breast lump checked. 

Luckily, she said, she trusted her gut and got a second opinion. 

Now, in a personal essay for TODAY.com, Hainsby reveals how her doctor originally downplayed her symptoms and shares tips for people who want to support someone going through cancer treatment. ➡️ Link in bio for the full story.

Determined to acknowledge the moments of progress along the way on the other side of my treatment. 
It’s not always linear, that’s for sure, but when there’s a win, I’m making a conscious decision to own it! I’ve learnt that life is too short to be embarrassed that you’re ‘bigging yourself up’. You should do that. You should be your biggest cheerleader, especially if you are working hard to better yourself. 
Today, I celebrate my first 45 minute LIVE ride in a LONG TIME. The energy that a class like that requires and deserves, just hasn’t been there for me. So, today is an achievement, and it felt great. I felt great. Proof that I am getting stronger and healthier everyday. What a privilege. 

My eyelashes fell out again this week, and my hair regrowth is WILD. My hairspray is working HARD for me at the moment on the bike. My body has gone through a lot, and I’m so proud of it, but I can’t deny that I don’t feel as strong in my body as I’ve always been used to, and that’s hard. It will come. Patience is something I’ve had no choice but to learn to accept.

Confidence wasn’t something I expected to find during this time, but I’ve put one foot in front of the other when things have been more tough than I ever could’ve imagined, and I’ve still found a way to keep showing up, despite really not wanting to at times. There’s a strength I’ve gained that I wish I didn’t need, but it has definitely changed me forever, and resilience has created confidence. Another win. It’s something I struggled with before.

So, I’ll take these small wins and moments of progress, and keep looking forward. One step at a time x

2 years since you asked me ‘Will you marry?’ and forgot to add the ‘me?’ and I forgot to actually say yes, but it was still so perfect for us 🤣🥰🎉💍 
The most common question we’re asked as a couple is, ‘When is the wedding?’
The truth is, if life had been kinder to us over the past year and a half, we’d probably be married or at least have a solid plan, but our focus has been elsewhere.
I really do think making that initial commitment to say ‘yes I do want to marry you, and yes you are the person I want to put the work and energy into every single day, even when it’s hard. In fact, even more so when life is hard’ is a beautiful chapter in life, and one to be acknowledged a little more. What I do know is that we are living out our vows before we’ve even officially made them. 
Through loss, grief, trauma, serious health battles, a new home, renovations, a full time job, and Jags, I am more certain than ever about our relationship and what we are lucky enough to be building together. We somehow find a way to keep smiling and finding joy, and I love and celebrate that, and where we are at today. Getting to love you is a privilege Benny Boy @benjaminalldis

Over the past 18 months our cover star Leanne Hainsby has - in no uncertain terms - been through it. 

Days after suddenly losing her best friend, Leanne felt a lump. A lump that, a month later, was confirmed to be grade three, early, triple-positive breast cancer - an aggressive, hormone-sensitive form of the disease.

Soon came her lumpectomy; IVF egg collection; chemotherapy - 12 rounds over three months - and radiotherapy.

Ongoing treatment includes a daily Tamoxifen tablet; anti-cancer injection Herceptin every three weeks; and hormone-suppressing injection, Zoladex, every 28 days.

Fortunately, in Leanne’s case, her treatment plan has been effective; doctors have told her that she’s now cancer free. 

But, in the latest episode of My Body, My Story, Leanne tells WH’s @roisin.dervishokane why, despite hitting these milestones, her cancer journey is far from over.

Head to the link in bio to watch the full episode 💛

2023 - The year I beat cancer. That’s my highlight. 

Time to give back. I’m running the London Marathon 2024 to raise money for @breastcancernow.

I’ve always LOVED the London marathon. I find it totally inspiring, hugely emotional and I’ve always wanted to do it. I’m completely terrified and at this point, can’t imagine finishing it.

I have always promised myself I would run it when I felt I had a ‘why’, and that time is now. Even better to do it in the city I live in, grew up in, and love.

I’m determined to change the conversation I have with myself about running. I CAN run, it’s just for some reason over the years I’ve lost my confidence with it, and refer to myself as someone who isn’t a runner 🙄.

Post cancer treatment, I have had this urge to go head first into the things I’ve told myself I can’t do, because I REALLY CAN, and when you go through hard times, you can’t believe you ever set yourself limits in certain areas of life.

I won’t be the best runner on the day, but I’ll be up there doing MY best AND raising money for a charity that has, and will continue to help thousands of people affected by breast cancer.

So, follow along for the journey, send any advice my way (pleassseeeee) and most importantly, donate if you can (link in bio)🏃‍♀️ ❤️ x
